Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take interim custody of the subject-matter of the dispute or to appoint a person to take such custody;
- to appoint a receiver to manage the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take such other interim measures as may be necessary for preserving evidence or for maintaining the status quo.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

IPC 141 refers to the Indian Penal Code, 1860. Section 141 of the IPC defines "unlawful assembly" as an assembly of five or more persons with the intention to commit an offense or to cause a disturbance of the public peace by using criminal force or show of criminal force.

According to Section 141 of the IPC:
"Unlawful assembly.- An assembly of five or more persons is designated an 'unlawful assembly' if the common object of the persons composing that assembly is-
First.- To commit any offence;
Second.- To commit any offence specified in Section 153A (offence related to promoting enmity between different groups on grounds of religion, race, place of birth, residence, language, etc.);
Third.- To commit any offence specified in Section 153B (offence related to imputations, assertions prejudicial to national integration);
Fourth.- To commit any offence punishable with imprisonment for a term of one year or more, or with fine, or both;
Fifth.- By means of criminal force, or show of criminal force, to any person, to take or obtain possession of any property, or to deprive him of the possession thereof, or to injure or annoy him, or to put him in fear of injury or annoyance;
Sixth.- By means of criminal force, or show of criminal force, to compel any person to do anything which he is not legally bound to do, or to omit to do anything which he is legally entitled to do;
Seventh.- To overawe the Government or the Central or any State Government by means of criminal force or show of criminal force;
Eighth.- To resist the execution of any law, or of any legal process;
Ninth.- To compel any person to do anything which he is not legally bound to do, by means of criminal intimidation;
Tenth.- To take or obtain possession of any property, or to deprive any person of the possession thereof, by means of criminal force or show of criminal force."

